{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3ef94238-d6bf-4ea3-a8c6-f753e9fc0b70","content":"Here's what you need to change for NuGet trusted publishing (OIDC):\n\n**1. On NuGet.org** — register your GitHub repo as a trusted publisher:\n- Go to your package → Manage → Publishing → Add Trusted Publisher\n- Specify your GitHub org/user, repo, and optionally the workflow file and environment\n\n**2. In your workflow:**\n\n```yaml\njobs:\n  publish:\n    runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n    permissions:\n      id-token: write  # Required for OIDC token\n      contents: read\n    steps:\n      - uses: actions/checkout@v4\n      - uses: actions/setup-dotnet@v4\n        with:\n          dotnet-version: '8.x'\n\n      - run: dotnet build -c Release\n      - run: dotnet pack -c Release\n\n      - name: Publish to NuGet\n        run: dotnet nuget push **/*.nupkg\n          --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n**Key changes:**\n| Before | After |\n|--------|-------|\n| `secrets.NUGET_API_KEY` in `--api-key` | No API key needed |\n| No `permissions` block | `id-token: write` required |\n| — | Register repo on NuGet.org as trusted publisher |\n\n**3. Remove** the `NUGET_API_KEY` secret from your repo settings once verified.\n\nThe OIDC token is automatically generated and exchanged with NuGet.org — no long-lived secrets to rotate.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9659fd78-8d84-4982-90d5-a0ea29f7519b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about switching from using a NuGet API key secret to NuGet trusted publishing (OIDC) in their GitHub Actions publish workflow. This is a general knowledge question about GitHub Actions and NuGet - I don't need to look at any specific files since there's no repository here. Let me provide a concise answer.\n\nNuGet trusted publishing (OIDC) allows GitHub Actions to authenticate with NuGet.org without storing long-lived API keys as secrets. Here's what they need to change:\n\n1. **On NuGet.org**: Configure trusted publishing for their package by adding a trusted publisher entry that links their GitHub repository/workflow.\n\n\n2. **In their workflow**: Add the `id-token: write` permission to the job, then use the OIDC token that GitHub Actions provides instead of the stored API key secret when pushing to NuGet.\n\nThe actual flow involves registering the repository as a trusted publisher on NuGet.org first, then in the workflow requesting an OIDC token and exchanging it for a short-lived NuGet API token to use with the push command.","outputTokens":831,"requestId":"2426:165513:15FA5EC:188BD6F:6A051EA3"},"id":"ca01f62f-2a8b-4ee3-a083-48a73be2e661","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:00:36.076Z","parentId":"fdc0a643-10d8-4498-bd63-8c26e940ce33"}
